1 SECTION 3. AMENDATORY 59 O.S. 2021, Section 519.3, as
2 amended by Section 4, Chapter 343, O.S.L. 2025 (59 O.S. Supp. 2025,
3 Section 519.3), is amended to read as follows:
4 Section 519.3. A. There is hereby created the Physician
5 Assistant Committee, which shall be composed of nine (9) members.
6 Five members of the Committee shall be physician assistants
7 appointed by the State Board of Medical Licensure and Supervision
8 from a list of qualified individuals submitted by the Oklahoma
9 Academy of Physician Assistants. One member shall be a physician
10 appointed by the Board from its membership. One member shall be a
11 physician appointed by the Board from a list of qualified
12 individuals submitted by the Oklahoma State Medical Association and
13 who is not a member of the Board. One member shall be a physician
14 appointed by the State Board of Osteopathic Examiners from its
15 membership. One member shall be a physician appointed by the State
16 Board of Osteopathic Examiners from a list of qualified individuals
17 submitted by the Oklahoma Osteopathic Association and who is not a
18 member of said board.
19 B. The term of office for each member of the Committee shall
20 be five (5) years.
21 C. The Committee shall meet at least quarterly. At the
22 initial meeting of each calendar year, the Committee members shall
23 elect a chair from the physician assistant members. The chair or
24 his or her designee shall represent the Committee at all meetings
(Floor Amendments Only) Date and Time Filed:
Untimely Amendment Cycle Extended Secondary Amendment

1 of the Board. Five members shall constitute a quorum for the
2 purpose of conducting official business of the Committee.
3 D. The State Board of Medical Licensure and Supervision is
4 hereby granted the power and authority to promulgate rules, which
5 are in accordance with the provisions of Section 519.1 et seq. of
6 this title, governing the requirements for licensure as a physician
7 assistant, as well as to establish standards for training, approve
8 institutions for training, and regulate the standards of practice
9 of a physician assistant after licensure, including the power of
10 revocation of a license.
11 E. The State Board of Medical Licensure and Supervision is
12 hereby granted the power and authority to investigate all
13 complaints, hold hearings, subpoena witnesses and initiate
14 prosecution concerning violations of Section 519.1 et seq. of this
15 title. When such complaints involve physicians licensed by the
16 State Board of Osteopathic Examiners, the State Board of
17 Osteopathic Examiners shall be officially notified of such
18 complaints.
19 F. 1. The Committee shall advise the Board on all matters
20 pertaining to the practice of physician assistants.
21 2. The Committee shall review and make recommendations to the
22 Board for approval of or other action on all applications for
23 licensure as a physician assistant and all applications to practice
24 which shall be approved by the Board. When considering applicants
(Floor Amendments Only) Date and Time Filed:
Untimely Amendment Cycle Extended Secondary Amendment

1 for licensure, to establish standards of training or approve
2 institutions for training, the Committee shall include the
3 Director, or designee, of all Physician Assistant educational
4 programs conducted by institutions of higher education in the state
5 as members.
6 3. The Committee shall assist and advise the Board in all
7 hearings involving physician assistants who are deemed to be in
8 violation of Section 519.1 et seq. of this title or the rules of
9 the Board.
10 SECTION 4. AMENDATORY 59 O.S. 2021, Section 519.4, as
11 amended by Section 7, Chapter 350, O.S.L. 2025 (59 O.S. Supp. 2025,
12 Section 519.4), is amended to read as follows:
13 Section 519.4. To be eligible for licensure as a physician
14 assistant pursuant to the provisions of Section 519.1 et seq. of
15 this title an applicant shall:
16 1. Have graduated from an accredited physician assistant
17 program recognized by the State Board of Medical Licensure and
18 Supervision;
19 2. Successfully pass an examination for physician assistants
20 recognized by the Board; and
21 3. Obtain a national criminal history background check; and
22 4. Successfully complete the jurisprudence examination of the
23 Board, in accordance with rules promulgated by the Board, upon
24 initial licensure or upon application to reenter practice.
